		<item>
		<title>Qwest CEO on VOIP regulation</title>
		<link>http://werblog.com/2003/12/qwest-ceo-on-voip-regulation/</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 18 Dec 2003 14:10:41 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[kwerb]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://werbach.com/wordpress/?p=1049</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Qwest CEO Dick Notebaert comes out in support of treating voice over IP as a largely unregulated &#8220;information service&#8221; in a Washington Times op-ed.&#160; Qwest is unique among the incumbent local phone giants, since it has a large Internet backbone and business services operation.&#160; Still, it&#8217;s good to see a telco CEO reject applying legacy ...<a class="post-readmore" href="http://werblog.com/2003/12/qwest-ceo-on-voip-regulation/">read more</a>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Qwest CEO Dick Notebaert comes out in support of treating voice over IP as a largely unregulated &#8220;information service&#8221; in a <a href="http://www.washtimes.com/op-ed/20031216-090337-5664r.htm">Washington Times op-ed</a>.&nbsp;<br />
Qwest is unique among the incumbent local phone giants, since it has a<br />
large Internet backbone and business services operation.&nbsp; Still,<br />
it&#8217;s good to see a telco CEO reject applying legacy regulation to<br />
VOIP.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The one point Notebaert&#8217;s op-ed doesn&#8217;t squarely address is whether<br />
VOIP should be subject to the inflated &#8220;access charges&#8221; that companies<br />
like Qwest charge to originate or terminate telephone traffic.&nbsp;<br />
The implication of classing VOIP as an information service is that<br />
access charges should not apply, and that&#8217;s the right result.&nbsp; </p>
]]></content:encoded>
